The principal MSS. containing the Mostellaria, or parts of it, are :—

(i) The Ambrosian palimpsest (Α), a MS. of the fourth or perhaps even of the third century A.D.-—one of the oldest MSS. of a Latin author in existence. But only parts of it are extant; of this play we have 354 lines, viz. 576-613‚ 630, 631, 632, 653—723, 759-796, 826—858, 891-1026 (44 lines), 1042-1073.

(ii) The three ‘Palatine' MSS. (B, C, D), dating from about the eleventh century ΑΛ).

(iii) The ‘Codex Lipsiensis’ (F), a MS. of the fifteenth century, and of no authority compared with that of the other MSS. referred to above.

Besides these MSS. we have occasional quotations of passages by grammarians and other scholars, which, being based on some ancient authority, sometimes throw light on the readings of MSS. which have been lost.

The first printed edition (the ‘editio princeps ') was pub- lished at Venice, 1472.

The textual notes at the end of this edition do not form an apparatus criticus3 they are limited to cases in which there is divergence of opinion among recent editors as to the true reading. But all readings for which the present editor is responsible are accompanied by a note. Readings of the Palatine MSS. are here given in black type and accompanied by the symbol P, minor discrepancies between B, C, and D being as a rule disregarded. The symbol P thus points to the readings of the arche—type of BCD—-a MS.
